JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 87
IS  - 3
SP  - 1213
EP  - 1260
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - I study the aggregate effects of labour market frictions in a small open economy where firms grow slowly and make fixed export investments. The model features interactions between dynamic investments in exporting and search frictions with job-to-job mobility. A calibration to Argentina’s economy matching data on firm growth, worker transitions between firms, and export dynamics suggests that the real income gains from lowering frictions in job-to-job transitions are about seven times larger than comparable reductions in frictions from unemployment. Barriers to worker mobility across firms matter for the real income gains of trade-cost reductions.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/restud/rdz063
